shimon peres ; (hebrew: שמעון פרס‎,  listen ; born szymon perski; august 2, 1923 – september 28, 2016) was an israeli politician who served both as ninth president of israel (2007–2014), and twice prime minister of israel, as well as interim prime minister, in the 1970s to the 1990s.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Shimon_Peres http://dbpedia.org/resource/Israel
= use of social-media = during his presidency (2007-2014), shimon peres was noted for his embrace of social media to communicate with the public, being described as 'israel's first social media president' which included producing comedic videos on his youtube channel such as 'be my friend for peace' and 'former israeli president shimon peres goes job hunting'.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Shimon_Peres http://dbpedia.org/resource/Israel
netanyahu stated: "shimon peres worked hard to establish this important facility, a facility which has been very important for israel's security for generations.."    published works   shimon peres is the author of 11 books, including: the next step (1965) david's sling (1970) (isbn 0-297-00083-7) and now tomorrow (1978) from these men: seven founders of the state of israel (1979) (isbn 0-671-61016-3) entebbe diary (1991) (isbn 965-248-111-4) the new middle east (1993) (isbn 0-8050-3323-8) battling for peace: a memoir (1995) (isbn 0-679-43617-0) for the future of israel (1998) (isbn 0-8018-5928-x) the imaginary voyage: with theodor herzl in israel (1999) (isbn 1-55970-468-3) ben gurion: a political life (2011) (isbn 978-0-8052-4282-9)    awards and recognition  1957: commander of the legion of honour.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Shimon_Peres http://dbpedia.org/resource/Israel

at the time, morrissey's best male friend was james maker; he would visit maker in london or they would meet up in manchester, where they visited the city's gay bars and gay clubs, in one case having to escape from a gang of gay bashers.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Morrissey http://dbpedia.org/resource/Manchester

he was born napoleone di buonaparte (italian: [napoleˈoːne di bwɔnaˈparte]) in corsica to a relatively modest family of italian ancestry from the minor nobility.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Napoleon http://dbpedia.org/resource/Corsica
early life   the ancestors of napoleon descended from minor italian nobility of tuscan origin who had come to corsica from liguria in the 16th century.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Napoleon http://dbpedia.org/resource/Corsica
napoleon was born the same year the republic of genoa, a former commune of italy, transferred corsica to france.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Napoleon http://dbpedia.org/resource/Corsica
napoleon's noble, moderately affluent background afforded him greater opportunities to study than were available to a typical corsican of the time.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Napoleon http://dbpedia.org/resource/Corsica
like many corsicans, napoleon spoke and read corsican (as his mother tongue) and italian (as the official language of corsica).	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Napoleon http://dbpedia.org/resource/Corsica
religion   napoleon's baptism took place in ajaccio on 21 july 1771; he was piously raised as a catholic but he never developed much faith.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Napoleon http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ajaccio

in may 1919, puyi noticed the protests in beijing generated by the may 4th movement as thousands of chinese university students protested against the decision by the great powers at the paris peace conference to award the former german concessions in shangdong province together with the former german colony of qingdao to japan.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Puyi http://dbpedia.org/resource/Beijing

on 15 march 1922, the betrothal of puyi and wanrong was announced in the newspapers, on 17 march wanrong took the train to beijing, and on 6 april puyi went to the qing family shrine to inform his ancestors that he would be married to her later that year.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Puyi http://dbpedia.org/resource/Beijing
the escape attempt failed when johnston vetoed it and refused to call a taxi and puyi was too frightened to live on the streets of beijing on his own.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Puyi http://dbpedia.org/resource/Beijing
in june 1927, zhang captured beijing and behr observed if puyi had more courage and returned to beijing, he might have been restored to the dragon throne.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Puyi http://dbpedia.org/resource/Beijing
semyonov claimed that he was only asking for puyi's financial support because of a temporary clash flow problem, and promised that once his cossacks took beijing he would repay all of the money puyi loaned him.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Puyi http://dbpedia.org/resource/Beijing
puyi later wrote "i thought beijing antique shops were full of such objects.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Puyi http://dbpedia.org/resource/Beijing

one of puyi's first acts upon returning to beijing was to visit the forbidden city as a tourist, where he pointed out to other tourists that many of the exhibits were the things he had used in his youth.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Puyi http://dbpedia.org/resource/Beijing

after the wedding was complete, puyi, wanrong, and his secondary consort wenxiu (whom he married the same night) went to the palace of earthly tranquility, where everything was red – the color of love and sex in china – and where emperors had traditionally consummated their marriages.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/Puyi http://dbpedia.org/resource/Wenxiu
woodhead stated that the only people who seemed to get along at puyi's court were wanrong and wenxiu, who were "like sisters".	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/Puyi http://dbpedia.org/resource/Wenxiu
the couple's relationship was good initially, and puyi showed preference over wenxiu for wanrong and displayed trust in her.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/Puyi http://dbpedia.org/resource/Wenxiu
wenxiu puyi's first choice for his wife was wenxiu, from the erdet (鄂爾德特) clan.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/Puyi http://dbpedia.org/resource/Wenxiu
although she was puyi's first choice, the four dowager consorts felt that wenxiu came from an unacceptable impoverished family and was not beautiful enough to be empress, so they told the court officials to ask puyi to choose again.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/Puyi http://dbpedia.org/resource/Wenxiu
the second time puyi chose wanrong, who became empress, while wenxiu was designated as consort shu (淑妃).	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/Puyi http://dbpedia.org/resource/Wenxiu

early life  yuan shikai was born in the village of zhangying (張營村), xiangcheng county, chenzhou prefecture, henan, though the clan later moved 16 kilometers southeast of xiangcheng to a hilly area that was easier to defend.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Yuan_Shikai http://dbpedia.org/resource/Henan
family  paternal grandfather yuan shusan (袁澍三) father yuan baozhong (袁保中) (1823–1874), courtesy name shouchen (受臣) uncle yuan baoqing (袁保慶) (1825–1873), courtesy name duchen (篤臣), pseudonym yanzhi (延之), yuan baozhong's younger brother wife yu yishang (于義上), daughter of yu ao (於鰲), a wealthy man from shenqiu county, henan; married yuan shikai in 1876; mother of yuan keding concubines lady shen (沈氏), previously a courtesan from suzhou lady lee (李氏), of korean origin; mother of yuan bozhen, yuan kequan, yuan keqi, yuan kejian, and yuan kedu lady kim (金氏), of korean origin; mother of yuan kewen, yuan keliang, yuan shuzhen, yuan huanzhen, and yuan sizhen lady o (吳氏), of korean origin; mother of yuan keduan, yuan zhongzhen, yuan cizhen, and yuan fuzhen lady yang (楊氏), mother of yuan kehuan, yuan kezhen, yuan kejiu, yuan ke'an, yuan jizhen, and yuan lingzhen lady ye (葉氏), previously a prostitute in nanjing; mother of yuan kejie, yuan keyou, yuan fuzhen, yuan qizhen, and yuan ruizhen lady zhang (張氏), originally from henan lady guo (郭氏), originally a prostitute from suzhou; mother of yuan kexiang, yuan kehe, and yuan huzhen lady liu (劉氏), originally a maid to yuan shikai's fifth concubine lady yang; mother of yuan kefan and yuan yizhen 17 sons yuan keding (袁克定) (1878–1958), courtesy name yuntai (雲台) yuan kewen (袁克文) (1889–1931), courtesy name baocen (豹岑) yuan keliang (袁克良), married a daughter of zhang baixi yuan keduan (袁克端), married he shenji (何慎基, daughter of he zhongjing (何仲璟)) yuan kequan (袁克權) (1898–1941), courtesy name gui'an (規庵), pseudonym baina (百衲), married a daughter of toteke duanfang (托忒克·端方) yuan kehuan (袁克桓), married chen zheng (陳徵, daughter of chen qitai (陳啟泰)) yuan keqi (袁克齊), married a daughter of sun baoqi yuan kezhen (袁克軫), married zhou ruizhu (周瑞珠, daughter of zhou fu (周馥)) yuan kejiu (袁克玖), married li shaofang (黎紹芳, 29 december 1906 – 15 april 1945, second daughter of li yuanhong) in 1934 yuan kejian (袁克堅), married a daughter of lu jianzhang (陸建章) yuan ke'an (袁克安), married li baohui (李寶慧) (daughter of li shiming (李士銘)) yuan kedu (袁克度), married a daughter of the wealthy luo yunzhang (羅雲章) yuan kexiang (袁克相), married firstly zhang shoufang (張壽芳, granddaughter of na tong (那桐)), married secondly chen sixing (陳思行, daughter of chen bingkun) yuan kejie (袁克捷), married lady wang (王氏) yuan kehe (袁克和), married a daughter of zhang diaochen (張調宸) yuan kefan (袁克藩), died young yuan keyou (袁克友), married a daughter of yu yunpeng (於雲鵬) 15 daughters  famous grandsons and great-grandsons yuan's grandson, luke chia-liu yuan (1912–2003) was a chinese-american physicist.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/child http://dbpedia.org/resource/Yuan_Shikai http://dbpedia.org/resource/Yuan_Keding

daniel webster (january 18, 1782 – october 24, 1852) was an american politician who represented new hampshire (1813–1817) and massachusetts (1823–1827) in the united states house of representatives; served as a senator from massachusetts (1827–1841, 1845–1850); and was the united states secretary of state under presidents william henry harrison (1841), john tyler (1841–1843), and millard fillmore (1850–1852).	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Daniel_Webster http://dbpedia.org/resource/New_Hampshire

biography    = early life = sarvepalli radhakrishnan was born in a telugu-speaking niyogi brahmin family, in a village thiruttani in the erstwhile chittoor district of madras presidency near the border of andhra pradesh and tamil nadu states.his surname was sarvepalli, for his forefathers were from sarvepalli, a village fifteen miles from nellore town of andhra pradesh.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Sarvepalli_Radhakrishnan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Thiruttani

the combination of his personal eccentricities and public policy failures produced criticism from such veteran revolutionaries as liu shaoqi, deng xiaoping, chen yun, and zhou enlai, who seemed less and less to share an enthusiasm for his presence or his vision of continuous revolutionary struggle.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Zhou_Enlai http://dbpedia.org/resource/Revolutionary
since his death, zhou enlai has been regarded as a skilled negotiator, a master of policy implementation, a devoted revolutionary, and a pragmatic statesman with an unusual attentiveness to detail and nuance.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Zhou_Enlai http://dbpedia.org/resource/Revolutionary

life and career    = 1971–1988: early life and career beginnings = selena quintanilla was born on april 16, 1971 in lake jackson, texas.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Selena http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lake_Jackson,_Texas
as of 2015, selena has sold over 65 million albums worldwide, making her the best-selling female artist in latin music history.	http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/gender http://dbpedia.org/resource/Selena female
selena was discovered by musician rick trevino, founder of the tejano music awards, where she won the female vocalist of the year award in 1987 and for nine consecutive years after.	http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/gender http://dbpedia.org/resource/Selena female
selena was often refused gigs at tejano venues because she was a female singer in a male-dominated music scene.	http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/gender http://dbpedia.org/resource/Selena female
selena became the third female artist to sell over 300,000 units in one week, after janet jackson and mariah carey.	http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/gender http://dbpedia.org/resource/Selena female
dreaming of you joined five of selena's studio albums on the billboard 200 chart simultaneously, making selena the first female artist in billboard history to do so.	http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/gender http://dbpedia.org/resource/Selena female
selena was named "best female vocalist of the '80s" and "best female vocalist of the '90s" at the 2010 tejano music awards.	http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/gender http://dbpedia.org/resource/Selena female
selena and her guitarist, chris pérez, eloped in april 1992 after her father raised concerns over their relationship.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/Selena http://dbpedia.org/resource/Chris_Pérez

zico also won another bronze medal with brazil in the 1979 copa américa.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Zico http://dbpedia.org/resource/Brazil

according to laskar, the “whole gamut” of rajiv gandhi’s foreign policy was “geared towards” making india “strong, independent, self-reliant and in the front rank of the nations of the world.”  according to laskar, rajiv gandhi’s diplomacy was “properly calibrated” so as to be “conciliatory and accommodating when required” and “assertive when the occasion demanded.”  in 1986, by request of the president of seychelles france-albert rené, gandhi sent india's navy to seychelles to oppose an attempted coup against rené.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rajiv_Gandhi http://dbpedia.org/resource/India
citing mckinsey as a source, the article stated that rajiv gandhi held 2.5 billion swiss francs in secret indian accounts in switzerland.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rajiv_Gandhi http://dbpedia.org/resource/India
in 1992, the rajiv gandhi national sadbhavana award was instituted by the indian national congress party.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rajiv_Gandhi http://dbpedia.org/resource/India

romário de souza faria (born 29 january 1966), known simply as romário (brazilian portuguese: [ʁoˈmaɾiu]), is a brazilian politician, who previously achieved worldwide fame as a professional footballer.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romário http://dbpedia.org/resource/Brazil
during the second half of his career romário played for clubs within the city of rio de janeiro in brazil.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romário http://dbpedia.org/resource/Brazil
at 34 years of age, romário had one of the best seasons in his career while winning the copa mercosur and the brazilian league title with vasco.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romário http://dbpedia.org/resource/Brazil
romário's performance was key in the mercosur final where vasco faced brazilian rivals palmeiras from são paulo.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romário http://dbpedia.org/resource/Brazil
romário received both the south american and brazilian footballer of the year awards.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romário http://dbpedia.org/resource/Brazil
in 2005, at 39 years of age, romário scored 22 goals in the brazilian championship, making him the league's top goalscorer for the third time.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romário http://dbpedia.org/resource/Brazil
= the ro-ro attack = in the subsequent years, romário formed, along with fellow brazilian forward ronaldo, a feared attacking combo, which was colloquially referred to as the ro-ro duo.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romário http://dbpedia.org/resource/Brazil
= last game for brazil = on 27 april 2005, romário played his last game with the brazilian national team in a friendly and celebratory match in são paulo.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romário http://dbpedia.org/resource/Brazil
political career   in the 2010 general election, romário was elected to the chamber of deputies on the brazilian socialist party ticket.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romário http://dbpedia.org/resource/Brazil
on february 19, 2014, romário announced that he would run for the brazilian senate in the 2014 general election, and the decision was officially confirmed in june.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romário http://dbpedia.org/resource/Brazil
in march 2018, romário announced he is to run for governor of rio de janeiro in the brazilian general election and would stand as a candidate for the centrist podemos party.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romário http://dbpedia.org/resource/Brazil
during the second half of his career romário played for clubs within the city of rio de janeiro in brazil.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romário http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rio_de_Janeiro

napoleon iii commissioned the grand reconstruction of paris, carried out by his prefect of the seine, baron haussmann.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Napoleon_III http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris
childhood and family    = early life = charles-louis napoleon bonaparte, later known as louis napoleon and then napoleon iii, was born in paris on the night of 20–21 april 1808.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Napoleon_III http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris
= reconstruction of paris (1854–70) =  napoleon iii began his regime by launching a series of enormous public works projects in paris, hiring tens of thousands of workers to improve the sanitation, water supply and traffic circulation of the city.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Napoleon_III http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris
for the nearly two decades of napoleon iii's reign, and for a decade afterwards, most of paris was an enormous construction site.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Napoleon_III http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris
napoleon iii also wanted to build new parks and gardens for the recreation and relaxation of the parisians, particularly those in the new neighbourhoods of the expanding city.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Napoleon_III http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris
napoleon iii transformed the bois de boulogne into a park (1852–58) to the west of paris: the bois de vincennes (1860–65) to the east; he created the parc des buttes-chaumont (1865–67) to the north, and the parc montsouris (1865–78) to the south.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Napoleon_III http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris
in april 1855, napoleon iii and eugénie went to england and were received by the queen; in turn, victoria visited paris, the first british monarch to do so in centuries.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Napoleon_III http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris
the rural departments still voted for napoleon iii's candidates, but in paris 63 percent of the votes went to anti-government republican candidates, with similar numbers in all the large cities.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Napoleon_III http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris
napoleon iii proposed returning to paris, realizing that he was doing no good for the army.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Napoleon_III http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris

a member of the non-emancipated jewish-romanian community, lazăr șăineanu stood for the haskalah ideas, and opted in favor of jewish assimilation into the romanian mainstream.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lazăr_Șăineanu http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romania
= 1899 parliamentary vote and self-exile = in order to facilitate the naturalization procedures, lazăr șăineanu eventually renounced judaism and accepted baptism in the romanian orthodox church.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lazăr_Șăineanu http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romania
literary critic laszlo alexandru passed a similar judgment: "lazăr șăineanu's disappearance from the romanian cultural space was received with an almost unanimous silence; but the emergence of lazare sainéan in parisian scientific research would not itself result, for the rest of his days, in the much coveted and entirely deserved university chair."	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lazăr_Șăineanu http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romania
= work in romanian folklore = much of lazăr șăineanu earliest contributions connected his linguistic research with his interest in romanian folklore.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lazăr_Șăineanu http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romania
lazăr șăineanu took additional care in preserving the integrity of the oral level of romanian literature in printed versions, and urged other folklorists interviewing storytellers to keep notes on the latter's special talents.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lazăr_Șăineanu http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romania

at the 51st annual grammy awards in february 2009, adele received the award for best new artist, in addition to the award for best female pop vocal performance for "chasing pavements", which was also nominated for record of the year and song of the year.	http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/gender http://dbpedia.org/resource/Adele female
in 2010, adele received a grammy nomination for best female pop vocal performance for "hometown glory."	http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/gender http://dbpedia.org/resource/Adele female
at the 2011 american music awards on 20 november, adele won three awards; favorite pop/rock female artist, favorite adult contemporary artist, and favorite pop/rock album for 21.	http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/gender http://dbpedia.org/resource/Adele female
adele received the brit award for best british female solo artist, and british album of the year presented to her by george michael.	http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/gender http://dbpedia.org/resource/Adele female
adele was also named top female artist.	http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/gender http://dbpedia.org/resource/Adele female
at the 2016 brit awards in london on 24 february, adele received the awards for british female solo artist, british album of the year for 25, british single of the year for "hello", and british global success, bringing her brit award wins to eight.	http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/gender http://dbpedia.org/resource/Adele female
however, adele called the comparisons between her and other female soul singers lazy, noting "we're a gender, not a genre".	http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/gender http://dbpedia.org/resource/Adele female
awards and achievements   at the 51st annual grammy awards in 2009, adele won awards in the categories of best new artist and best female pop vocal performance.	http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/gender http://dbpedia.org/resource/Adele female
the success of her debut album 19 saw adele nominated for three brit awards in the categories of best british female, best british single and best british breakthrough act.	http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/gender http://dbpedia.org/resource/Adele female
on the week ending 3 march 2012, adele became the first solo female artist to have three singles in the top 10 of the billboard hot 100 at the same time, and the first female artist to have two albums in the top 5 of the billboard 200 and two singles in the top 5 of the billboard hot 100 simultaneously.	http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/gender http://dbpedia.org/resource/Adele female

nero (; latin: nero claudius caesar augustus germanicus; 15 december 37 – 9 june 68 ad) was the last roman emperor of the julio-claudian dynasty.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/parent http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nero http://dbpedia.org/resource/Claudius
nero's mother, agrippina the younger, was likely implicated in claudius' death and nero's nomination as emperor.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/parent http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nero http://dbpedia.org/resource/Claudius
after nero's adoption, "claudius" became part of his name: nero claudius caesar drusus germanicus.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/parent http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nero http://dbpedia.org/resource/Claudius
barrett writes that poppaea seems to serve as a "literary device, utilized [by tacitus] because [he] could see no plausible explanation for nero's conduct and also incidentally [served] to show that nero, like claudius, had fallen under the malign influence of a woman."	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/parent http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nero http://dbpedia.org/resource/Claudius
these sources contradict one another on a number of events in nero's life including the death of claudius, the death of agrippina, and the roman fire of 64, but they are consistent in their condemnation of nero.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/parent http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nero http://dbpedia.org/resource/Claudius
nero's depiction in tacitus' annals nero claudius drusus germanicus entry in the illustrated history of the roman empire.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/parent http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nero http://dbpedia.org/resource/Claudius
when he turned 16, nero married claudius' daughter (his own step-sister), claudia octavia.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nero http://dbpedia.org/resource/Claudia_Octavia
travelling in disguise, nero and four loyal freedmen, epaphroditos, phaon, neophytus, and sporus, reached the villa, where nero ordered them to dig a grave for him.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nero http://dbpedia.org/resource/Sporus
according to tacitus, the source of conflict between nero and his mother was nero's affair with poppaea sabina.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nero http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poppaea_Sabina

hun sen (khmer: ហ៊ុន សែន; born 5 august 1952) is the prime minister of cambodia, president of the cambodian people's party (cpp), and member of parliament (mp) for kandal.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hun_Sen http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cambodia
hun sen has accumulated highly centralized power within cambodia, including a personal guard said to have capabilities rivalling those of the country's regular army, making coup attempts virtually impossible.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hun_Sen http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cambodia
when the khmer rouge regime was defeated, hun sen was appointed as deputy prime minister and foreign minister of the vietnamese-installed people's republic of kampuchea/state of cambodia (prk/soc) in 1979.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hun_Sen http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cambodia
as foreign minister and then prime minister, hun sen played a pivotal role in the 1991 paris peace talks, which brokered peace in cambodia.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hun_Sen http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cambodia
in response, hun sen launched the 1997 cambodian coup, replacing ranariddh with ung hout as the first prime minister and maintaining his position as the second prime minister, a situation which lasted until the cpp's victory in the 1998 election, after which he became the country's sole prime minister.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hun_Sen http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cambodia
on 6 may 2013, hun sen declared his intention to rule cambodia until the age of 74.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hun_Sen http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cambodia
after the 2013 election results, disputed by hun sen's opposition, one person was killed and others injured during protests in cambodia's capital, where a reported 20,000 protesters gathered, some clashing with riot police.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hun_Sen http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cambodia
us congressman ed royce responded to the report of violence in cambodia by calling for hun sen to step down, saying that the cambodian people deserve a better leader.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hun_Sen http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cambodia
furthermore, hun sen vowed a constitutional amendment which could potentially see the opposition cambodia national rescue party dissolved.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hun_Sen http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cambodia
hun sen and his supporters reject such charges, saying that he only represented the cambodian people.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hun_Sen http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cambodia
hun sen's government has been responsible for leasing 45% of the total landmass in cambodia—primarily to foreign investors—in the years 2007-08, threatening more than 150,000 cambodians with eviction.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hun_Sen http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cambodia
hun sen was implicated in corruption related to cambodia's oil wealth and mineral resources in the global witness 2009 report on cambodia.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hun_Sen http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cambodia
hun sen: strongman of cambodia.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hun_Sen http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cambodia
personal life  hun sen is married to bun rany.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hun_Sen http://dbpedia.org/resource/Bun_Rany

also in 2012, aaliyah was ranked at number 10 on complex magazine's 100 hottest female singers of all-time list and number 22 on their 90 hottest women of the 90's list.	http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/gender http://dbpedia.org/resource/Aaliyah female

christopher john farley of time magazine described the album as a "beautifully restrained work", noting that aaliyah's "girlish, breathy vocals rode calmly on r. kelly's rough beats".	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/Aaliyah http://dbpedia.org/resource/R._Kelly

in 2014, jomo hankerson stated that aaliyah "got villainized" over her relationship with r. kelly and the scandal over the marriage made it difficult to find producers for her second album.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/Aaliyah http://dbpedia.org/resource/R._Kelly
aaliyah was known to avoid answering questions regarding r. kelly following the professional split.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/Aaliyah http://dbpedia.org/resource/R._Kelly
a spokeswoman for aaliyah said in 2000 that when "r. kelly comes up, she doesn't even speak his name, and nobody's allowed to ask about it at all".	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/Aaliyah http://dbpedia.org/resource/R._Kelly
aaliyah's mother diane haughton reflected that everything "that went wrong in her life" began with her relationship with r. kelly.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/Aaliyah http://dbpedia.org/resource/R._Kelly

= 1823: marriage and third arctic expedition = in 1823, after returning to england, sir john franklin married the poet eleanor anne porden.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/John_Franklin http://dbpedia.org/resource/Eleanor_Anne_Porden
early life   while his paternal family was from the town of velletri, approximately 40 kilometres (25 mi) from rome, augustus was born in the city of rome on 23 september 63 bc.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Augustus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rome
augustus was granted sole imperium within the city of rome itself, in addition to being granted proconsular imperium maius and tribunician authority for life.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Augustus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rome
in addition, the credit was given to augustus for each subsequent roman military victory after this time, because the majority of rome's armies were stationed in imperial provinces commanded by augustus through the legatus who were deputies of the princeps in the provinces.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Augustus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rome
this meant that augustus was the only individual able to receive a triumph, a tradition that began with romulus, rome's first king and first triumphant general.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Augustus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rome
after a theatrical display of refusal before the senate, augustus finally accepted authority over rome's grain supply "by virtue of his proconsular imperium", and ended the crisis almost immediately.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Augustus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rome
it was not until ad 8 that a food crisis of this sort prompted augustus to establish a praefectus annonae, a permanent prefect who was in charge of procuring food supplies for rome.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Augustus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rome
to ensure security of the empire's eastern flank, augustus stationed a roman army in syria, while his skilled stepson tiberius negotiated with the parthians as rome's diplomat to the east.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Augustus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rome
however, maria brosius explains that augustus used the return of the standards as propaganda symbolizing the submission of parthia to rome.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Augustus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rome
an enormous funerary procession of mourners traveled with augustus' body from nola to rome, and on the day of his burial all public and private businesses closed for the day.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Augustus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rome
the augustan era poets virgil and horace praised augustus as a defender of rome, an upholder of moral justice, and an individual who bore the brunt of responsibility in maintaining the empire.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Augustus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rome
in the beginning of his annals, the roman historian tacitus (c. 56–c.117) wrote that augustus had cunningly subverted republican rome into a position of slavery.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Augustus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rome
he continued to say that, with augustus' death and swearing of loyalty to tiberius, the people of rome simply traded one slaveholder for another.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Augustus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rome
the anglo-irish writer jonathan swift (1667–1745), in his discourse on the contests and dissentions in athens and rome, criticized augustus for installing tyranny over rome, and likened what he believed great britain's virtuous constitutional monarchy to rome's moral republic of the 2nd century bc.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Augustus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rome
augustus brought a far greater portion of the empire's expanded land base under consistent, direct taxation from rome, instead of exacting varying, intermittent, and somewhat arbitrary tributes from each local province as augustus' predecessors had done.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Augustus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rome
= building projects =  on his deathbed, augustus boasted "i found a rome of bricks; i leave to you one of marble."	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Augustus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rome
the corinthian order of architectural style originating from ancient greece was the dominant architectural style in the age of augustus and the imperial phase of rome.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Augustus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rome
suetonius once commented that rome was unworthy of its status as an imperial capital, yet augustus and agrippa set out to dismantle this sentiment by transforming the appearance of rome upon the classical greek model.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Augustus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rome
legally, it was closed to patricians, a status that augustus had acquired some years earlier when adopted by julius caesar.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/parent http://dbpedia.org/resource/Augustus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Julius_Caesar
augustus was intelligent, decisive, and a shrewd politician, but he was not perhaps as charismatic as julius caesar, and was influenced on occasion by his third wife, livia (sometimes for the worse).	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/parent http://dbpedia.org/resource/Augustus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Julius_Caesar
commonly repeated lore has it that august has 31 days because augustus wanted his month to match the length of julius caesar's july, but this is an invention of the 13th century scholar johannes de sacrobosco.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/parent http://dbpedia.org/resource/Augustus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Julius_Caesar
name  as a consequence of roman customs, society, and personal preference augustus (; classical latin: [awˈɡʊstʊs]) was known by many names throughout his life: gaius octavius thurinus (): he received his birth name, after his biological father, in 63 bc.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/parent http://dbpedia.org/resource/Augustus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Gaius_Octavius
tiberius, augustus' eldest son by marriage to livia, was the only other general to receive a triumph—for victories in germania in 7 bc.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/Augustus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Livia
augustus also showed favor to his stepsons, livia's children from her first marriage nero claudius drusus germanicus (henceforth referred to as drusus) and tiberius claudius (henceforth tiberius), granting them military commands and public office, though seeming to favor drusus.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/Augustus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Livia
early life    = youth: 1926–46 = paul-michel foucault was born on 15 october 1926 in the city of poitiers, west-central france, as the second of three children in a prosperous and socially conservative upper-middle-class family.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Michel_Foucault http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poitiers

pompey's father, gnaeus pompeius strabo, was a wealthy equestrian from picenum (in south and north of the modern regions of the marche and abruzzo, in central italy, on the adriatic coast).	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pompey http://dbpedia.org/resource/Picenum
pompey raised three legions in picenum to support sulla's march on rome against the marian regime of gnaeus papirius carbo and gaius marius the younger.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pompey http://dbpedia.org/resource/Picenum
lepidus openly revolts against the senate a few months later; pompey suppresses the rebellion with an army raised from picenum and puts down the rebellion, killing the senior legate marcus junius brutus, father of brutus who assassinated julius caesar.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pompey http://dbpedia.org/resource/Picenum
gnaeus pompeius magnus (classical latin: [ˈgnae̯.ʊs pɔmˈpɛj.jʊs ˈmaŋ.nʊs]; 29 september 106 bc – 28 september 48 bc), usually known in english as pompey  or pompey the great, was a military and political leader of the late roman republic.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pompey http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roman_Republic
pompey and mucia had three children: the eldest, gnaeus pompey (pompey the younger), pompeia magna, a daughter, and sextus pompey, the younger son.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/child http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pompey http://dbpedia.org/resource/Sextus_Pompey
pompey and mucia had three children: the eldest, gnaeus pompey (pompey the younger), pompeia magna, a daughter, and sextus pompey, the younger son.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/child http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pompey http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pompeia_Magna
marriages and offspring  first wife, antistia second wife, aemilia scaura (sulla's stepdaughter) third wife, mucia tertia (whom he divorced for adultery, according to cicero's letters) offspring of marriage between mucia and pompey magnus gnaeus pompeius, executed in 45 bc, after the battle of munda pompeia magna, married to faustus cornelius sulla; ancestor of gnaeus pompeius magnus (claudia antonia's first husband) sextus pompey, who would rebel in sicily against augustus  fourth wife julia (daughter of caesar) fifth wife, cornelia metella (daughter of metellus scipio)    chronology of pompey's life and career  106 bc september 29 – born in picenum 83 bc – aligns with sulla, after his return from the first mithridatic war against king mithridates vi of pontus; 83 bc – pompey raises a legion and cavalry in hopes of joining sulla 82 bc – marriage to aemilia scaura at the behest of sulla, aemilia is already pregnant and eventually dies during childbirth 82–81 bc – defeats gaius marius's allies in sicily (autumn of 82 bc) and africa after his victory in sicily 81 bc – returns to rome and celebrates first triumph 80 bc – pompey marries mucia of the mucii scaevolae family 79 bc – pompey supports the election of marcus aemilius lepidus.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/child http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pompey http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pompeia_Magna
following his preliminary bouts with his accuser, the judge took a liking to pompey and offered his daughter, antistia in marriage.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pompey http://dbpedia.org/resource/Antistia
he and his wife, metella, persuaded pompey to divorce antistia and marry sulla's stepdaughter aemilia scaura.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pompey http://dbpedia.org/resource/Aemilia_Scaura

francesco petrarca (italian: [franˈtʃesko peˈtrarka]; july 20, 1304 – july 20, 1374), commonly anglicized as petrarch (), was an italian scholar and poet in renaissance italy, who was one of the earliest humanists.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Petrarch http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
petrarch's sonnets were admired and imitated throughout europe during the renaissance and became a model for lyrical poetry.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Petrarch http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet

pakistan suffered a decisive defeat in the bangladesh liberation war of 1971, resulting in the dissolution of eastern command, pakistani loss of geopolitical influence in the muslim world, and the secession of east pakistan as bangladesh– thus yahya khan's rule is widely regarded as a leading cause of the break-up of the unity of pakistan.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Yahya_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pakistan
once ayub handed over power to yahya khan on 25 march 1969 yahya inherited a two-decade constitutional problem of inter-provincial ethnic rivalry between the punjabi-pashtun-mohajir dominated west pakistan province and the ethnically bengali muslim east pakistan province.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Yahya_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pakistan
all these were complex problems and the seeds of pakistan army's defeat and humiliation in december 1971 lay in the fact that yahya khan blundered unwittingly into the thankless task of fixing the problems of pakistan's political and administrative system which had been accumulating for 20 years and had their actual origins in the pre-1947 british policies towards the bengali muslims.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Yahya_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pakistan
yahya khan attempted to solve pakistan's constitutional and inter-provincial/regional rivalry problems once he took over power from ayub khan in march 1969.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Yahya_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pakistan

lars løkke rasmussen (danish: [lɑːs ˈløɡə ˈʁɑsmusn̩]; born 15 may 1964) is a danish politician and current prime minister of denmark since june 2015.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lars_Løkke_Rasmussen http://dbpedia.org/resource/Denmark
municipal reform of 2007  as minister of the interior and health, lars løkke rasmussen spearheaded the municipal reform that reduced denmark's 271 municipalities to 98, and abolished the 14 counties and replaced them with five regions.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lars_Løkke_Rasmussen http://dbpedia.org/resource/Denmark
as deputy of the largest party in the government, lars løkke rasmussen thus took over the post as prime minister of denmark.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lars_Løkke_Rasmussen http://dbpedia.org/resource/Denmark
an opinion poll released on the day of lars løkke rasmussen's takeover revealed that danes believed that he only beat helle thorning-schmidt as the person best suited for bringing denmark through the financial crisis, and that thorning-schmidt would have been better suited to combatting unemployment, reducing hospital waiting lists, securing the welfare society of the future, and representing denmark internationally.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lars_Løkke_Rasmussen http://dbpedia.org/resource/Denmark
in 2013, the global green growth institute (gggi) was criticized by two member countries for its financial management: norway withheld $10 million in donations, citing excessive spending on flights and food by gggi former council chairman lars løkke rasmussen, and both norway and denmark demanded an audit of the organization's finances before renewing support for 2014.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lars_Løkke_Rasmussen http://dbpedia.org/resource/Denmark

emigration to ireland, abandonment  a complex series of conflicts and events led to lafcadio hearn being moved from greece to ireland, where he was abandoned first by his mother (leaving him in the care of her husband's aunt), then his father, and finally by his father's aunt, who had been appointed his official guardian.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lafcadio_Hearn http://dbpedia.org/resource/Greece

personal background and life  paul-henri spaak was born on 25 january 1899 in schaerbeek, belgium, to the distinguished belgian family spaak, of a branch that immigrated to belgium in the 17th century, originally from bohuslän in sweden.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paul-Henri_Spaak http://dbpedia.org/resource/Schaerbeek
another noted members of his family included his uncle, paul-emile janson, who served as prime minister of belgium from 1937 to 1938 and his niece, catherine spaak, a movie star, paul-henri spaak and his wife marguerite malevez had two daughters: antoinette spaak, the first belgian woman to lead a political party, the democratic front of francophones, and a son, the diplomat fernand spaak.	http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/gender http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paul-Henri_Spaak male

life  oliver lodge was born in 1851 at 'the views' penkhull, then an elevated rural village high above the emerging potteries of north staffordshire  in what is now stoke-on-trent, and educated at adams' grammar school, newport, shropshire.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Oliver_Lodge http://dbpedia.org/resource/Penkhull
he was the eldest of eight sons and a daughter of oliver lodge (1826–1884) – later a ball clay merchant at wolstanton, staffordshire – and his wife, grace, née heath (1826–1879).	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Oliver_Lodge http://dbpedia.org/resource/Staffordshire

john ardis cawthon (march 16, 1907 – october 5, 1984) was an educator and regional historian from ruston in lincoln parish in north louisiana, who was affiliated with louisiana tech university from 1939–1940, 1948, and from january 12, 1954, until retirement on may 31, 1972.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/John_Ardis_Cawthon http://dbpedia.org/resource/Historian

seyyed mohammad khatami (persian: سید محمد خاتمی‎, pronounced [ sejˈjed mohæmˈmæde xɒːtæˈmiː] ( listen); born 14 october 1943) is an iranian scholar, shia theologian, and reformist politician.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Mohammad_Khatami http://dbpedia.org/resource/Iran
on 30 january 2006, mohammad khatami officially inaugurated the office of the "international institute of dialogue among civilizations", an ngo with offices in iran and europe that he will be heading, after his retirement from the government.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Mohammad_Khatami http://dbpedia.org/resource/Iran
on 7 september 2006, during a visit to washington, mohammad khatami called for dialogue between the united states and iran.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Mohammad_Khatami http://dbpedia.org/resource/Iran

gotthold ephraim lessing (german: [ˈlɛsɪŋ]; 22 january 1729 – 15 february 1781) was a german writer, philosopher, dramatist, publicist and art critic, and one of the most outstanding representatives of the enlightenment era.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Gotthold_Ephraim_Lessing http://dbpedia.org/resource/Publicist

gotthold ephraim lessing (german: [ˈlɛsɪŋ]; 22 january 1729 – 15 february 1781) was a german writer, philosopher, dramatist, publicist and art critic, and one of the most outstanding representatives of the enlightenment era.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Gotthold_Ephraim_Lessing http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dramatist
anne of brittany (french: anne de bretagne; breton: anna breizh) (25/26 january 1477 – 9 january 1514) was duchess of brittany from 1488 until her death, and queen consort of france from 1491 to 1498 and from 1499 to her death.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Anne_of_Brittany http://dbpedia.org/resource/Brittany
anne of brittany had a limited role in france and brittany and sometimes had to accept being separated from her children in infancy.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Anne_of_Brittany http://dbpedia.org/resource/Brittany
representations and social legacy   even while she was alive, the royal propaganda of charles viii and of louis xii depicted anne of brittany as a perfect queen, a symbol of union and peace between the kingdom of france and the duchy of brittany (the popular tradition of the "good duchess").	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Anne_of_Brittany http://dbpedia.org/resource/Brittany
many myths now surround anne of brittany, as a woman forced into an arranged marriage with charles viii, the duchess of brittany committed to the independence and happiness of her country, or otherwise of a queen symbol of union and peace between brittany and france.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Anne_of_Brittany http://dbpedia.org/resource/Brittany

posthumously)    honours and awards    = honours = 1977: knight of the order of orange-nassau (netherlands) 1992: officer of the order of orange-nassau (netherlands) 1997: commander of the order of the netherlands lion 2001: knight of the order of arts and letters (france) 2002: officer's cross of the order of merit of the federal republic of germany   = awards = 1951: reina prinsen geerligs award, for the novel "archibald strohalm" 1957: de bijenkorf literary award, for the novel "the black light" 1957: anne frank award, for novel "archibald strohalm" 1961: athos prize, for lifetime achievement 1961: anv-visser neerlandia prize, for the play "tanchelijn" 1963: vijverberg prize, for the report "criminal case 40/61" 1977: constantijn huygens prize, for lifetime achievement 1977: cestoda prize 1977: p. c. hooft award, for lifetime achievement 1986: deep sea award, for the novel "the assault" 1993: multatuli prize, for the novel "the discovery of heaven" 1993: mecca award, for the novel "the discovery of heaven" 1995: dutch literature prize, for his whole oeuvre 1999: libris prize, for the novel the procedure 1999: prix jean monnet de littérature européenne, french prize for the novel "the discovery of heaven" 2003: inktaap prize, for the novel "siegfried" 2003: premio flaiano, italian prize for literature 2007: prix européen des jeunes lecteurs, french prize for the novel "siegfried" 2007: honorary doctorate from the university of amsterdam 2007: premio nonino, italian prize for literature 2007: prize for best dutch novel of all time, for the novel "the discovery of heaven" 2009: golden century award, for his entire oeuvre   = planetoid = mulisch was honored with a planetoid in his name on 12 october 2006 (see 10251 mulisch)    references     external links władziu valentino liberace (may 16, 1919 – february 4, 1987), known as liberace, was an american pianist, singer, and actor.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Liberace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pianist
in the batman television series in 1966 with adam west and burt ward, liberace played a dual role as concert pianist chandell and his gangster-like twin harry, who was extorting chandell into a life of crime as "fingers", in the episodes "the devil's fingers" and "the dead ringers", both written by lorenzo semple jr., who had developed batman for television.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Liberace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pianist
", and also included his interpretations of the classical piano repertoire such as chopin and liszt, although many fans of classical music widely criticized them (as well as liberace's skills as a pianist in general) for being "pure fluff with minimal musicianship".	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Liberace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pianist
in 1982, scott thorson, liberace's 22-year-old former chauffeur and live-in lover of five years, sued the pianist for $113 million in palimony after he was let go by liberace.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Liberace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pianist

percy mahendra rajapaksa, mp (sinhalese: පර්සි මහේන්ද්‍ර රාජපක්ෂ; born 18 november 1945), more commonly known as mahinda rajapaksa (sinhalese: මහින්ද රාජපක්ෂ, tamil: மஹிந்த ராஜபக்ஷ) pronounced [maˈhində ˈraːɟəˌpakʂə] is a sri lankan politician who served as the sixth president of sri lanka from 19 november 2005 to 9 january 2015.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Mahinda_Rajapaksa http://dbpedia.org/resource/Sri_Lanka
presidency  mahinda rajapaksa was chosen by sri lanka freedom party to contest with former prime minister and opposition leader, ranil wickremesinghe, the leader of the united national party in this presidential election held on 17 november 2005.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Mahinda_Rajapaksa http://dbpedia.org/resource/Sri_Lanka
the sri lanka government declared total victory on 18 may 2009. on 19 may 2009 president mahinda rajapaksa delivered a victory address to the parliament and declared that sri lanka is liberated from terrorism.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Mahinda_Rajapaksa http://dbpedia.org/resource/Sri_Lanka

publius vergilius maro (classical latin: [ˈpuː.blɪ.ʊs wɛrˈɡɪ.lɪ.ʊs ˈma.roː]; traditional dates october 15, 70 bc – september 21, 19 bc), usually called virgil or vergil  in english, was an ancient roman poet of the augustan period.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Virgil http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
virgil is traditionally ranked as one of rome's greatest poets.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Virgil http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
although the commentaries no doubt record much factual information about virgil, some of their evidence can be shown to rely on inferences made from his poetry and allegorizing; thus, virgil's biographical tradition remains problematic.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Virgil http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
after considering briefly a career in rhetoric and law, the young virgil turned his talents to poetry.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Virgil http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
virgil is credited in the eclogues with establishing arcadia as a poetic ideal that still resonates in western literature and visual arts and setting the stage for the development of latin pastoral by calpurnius siculus, nemesianus, and later writers.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Virgil http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
virgil came to know many of the other leading literary figures of the time, including horace, in whose poetry he is often mentioned, and varius rufus, who later helped finish the aeneid.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Virgil http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
in handling this theme, virgil follows in the didactic ("how to") tradition of the greek poet hesiod's works and days and several works of the later hellenistic poets.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Virgil http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
ancient scholars, such as servius, conjectured that the aristaeus episode replaced, at the emperor's request, a long section in praise of virgil's friend, the poet gallus, who was disgraced by augustus, and who committed suicide in 26 bc.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Virgil http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
ancient commentators noted that virgil seems to divide the aeneid into two sections based on the poetry of homer; the first six books were viewed as employing the odyssey as a model while the last six were connected to the iliad.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Virgil http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
later views and reception    = in antiquity =  the works of virgil almost from the moment of their publication revolutionized latin poetry.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Virgil http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
poets following virgil often refer intertextually to his works to generate meaning in their own poetry.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Virgil http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
indeed, silius is known to have bought virgil's tomb and worshipped the poet.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Virgil http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
= late antiquity and middle ages =  even as the western roman empire collapsed, literate men acknowledged that virgil was a master poet.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Virgil http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
gregory of tours read virgil, whom he quotes in several places, along with some other latin poets, though he cautions that "we ought not to relate their lying fables, lest we fall under sentence of eternal death."	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Virgil http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
dante also mentions virgil in de vulgari eloquentia, along with ovid, lucan and statius, as one of the four regulati poetae (ii, vi, 7).	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Virgil http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet

trajan's birthplace of italica was founded as a roman military colony of italian settlers in 206 bc, though it is unknown when the ulpii arrived there.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Trajan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Italica
as the details of trajan's military career are obscure, it is only sure that in 89, as legate of legio vii gemina in hispania tarraconensis, he supported domitian against an attempted coup.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Trajan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hispania
trajan built several new buildings, monuments and roads in italia and his native hispania.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Trajan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hispania
also, it is possible that the attachment of trajan to an expansionist policy was supported by a powerful circle of conservative senators from hispania committed to a policy of imperial expansion, first among them being the all-powerful licinius sura.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Trajan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hispania
although julian's scathing comments on the matter reflect a change of mores that began with the severan dynasty, an earlier author, cassius dio, already makes reference to trajan's marked personal preference for the male sex.	http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/gender http://dbpedia.org/resource/Trajan male
trajan (; latin: imperator caesar nerva trajanus divi nervae filius augustus; 18 september 53 – 8 august 117 ad) was roman emperor from 98 to 117 ad.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/parent http://dbpedia.org/resource/Trajan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nerva
there are hints, however, in contemporary literary sources that trajan's adoption was imposed on nerva.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/parent http://dbpedia.org/resource/Trajan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nerva
if this was what actually occurred, trajan would be a usurper, and the notion of a natural continuity between nerva's and trajan's reigns would be an ex post fiction developed later by historians such as tacitus.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/parent http://dbpedia.org/resource/Trajan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nerva

marcus tullius cicero (; classical latin: [ˈmaːr.kʊs ˈtʊl.lɪ.ʊs ˈkɪ.kɛ.roː]; 3 january 106 bc – 7 december 43 bc) was a roman politician and lawyer, who served as consul in the year 63 bc.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cicero http://dbpedia.org/resource/Politician
cicero's fellow students were gaius marius minor, servius sulpicius rufus (who became a famous lawyer, one of the few whom cicero considered superior to himself in legal matters), and titus pomponius.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cicero http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lawyer
cicero started his career as a lawyer around 83–81 bc.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cicero http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lawyer
cicero was therefore educated in the teachings of the ancient greek philosophers, poets and historians; he obtained much of his understanding of the theory and practice of rhetoric from the greek poet archias and from the greek rhetorician apollonius.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cicero http://dbpedia.org/resource/Philosopher
in atticus's large library, cicero read everything that the greek philosophers had written about overcoming grief, "but my sorrow defeats all consolation."	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cicero http://dbpedia.org/resource/Philosopher
cicero hoped that his son marcus would become a philosopher like him, but marcus himself wished for a military career.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cicero http://dbpedia.org/resource/Philosopher
cicero sent him to athens to study as a disciple of the peripatetic philosopher kratippos in 48 bc, but he used this absence from "his father's vigilant eye" to "eat, drink and be merry."	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cicero http://dbpedia.org/resource/Philosopher
charting a middle path between the competing attic and asiatic styles, cicero would ultimately become considered second only to demosthenes among history's orators.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cicero http://dbpedia.org/resource/Orator
on the conclusion of this case, cicero came to be considered the greatest orator in rome.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cicero http://dbpedia.org/resource/Orator
michael parenti admits cicero's abilities as an orator, but finds him a vain, pompous and hypocritical personality who, when it suited him, could show public support for popular causes that he privately despised.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cicero http://dbpedia.org/resource/Orator
cicero was therefore educated in the teachings of the ancient greek philosophers, poets and historians; he obtained much of his understanding of the theory and practice of rhetoric from the greek poet archias and from the greek rhetorician apollonius.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cicero http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet

omar sharif (arabic: عمر الشريف‎, egyptian arabic pronunciation: [ˈʕomɑɾ eʃʃɪˈɾiːf]; born michel dimitri chalhoub [miˈʃel dɪˈmitɾi ʃælˈhuːb]; 10 april 1932 – 10 july 2015) was an egyptian actor.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Omar_Sharif http://dbpedia.org/resource/Egypt
early life  omar sharif, whose adopted surname means "noble" or "nobleman", was born as michel dimitri chalhoub in alexandria, egypt, to a family of melkite catholic descent: he belonged to a small ethnocultural minority known as the damascene 'antiochian' greek catholics of egypt (rum katuleek al shawamm), an offshoot of the greek orthodox church of antioch his father, joseph chalhoub, a precious woods merchant originally from damascus, syria, moved to the port city of alexandria in the early 20th century, where sharif was later born.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Omar_Sharif http://dbpedia.org/resource/Egypt
early life  omar sharif, whose adopted surname means "noble" or "nobleman", was born as michel dimitri chalhoub in alexandria, egypt, to a family of melkite catholic descent: he belonged to a small ethnocultural minority known as the damascene 'antiochian' greek catholics of egypt (rum katuleek al shawamm), an offshoot of the greek orthodox church of antioch his father, joseph chalhoub, a precious woods merchant originally from damascus, syria, moved to the port city of alexandria in the early 20th century, where sharif was later born.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Omar_Sharif http://dbpedia.org/resource/Alexandria

= milestones = his jersey number 30 has been retired by the granby bisons his jersey number 33 has been retired by the colorado avalanche and the montreal canadiens in 1998, he was ranked number 22 on the hockey news' list of the 100 greatest hockey players the colorado sports hall of fame 2004 quebec major junior hockey league hall of fame 2004 hockey hall of fame inductee 2006 was ranked #5 in the hockey news' the top 60 since 1967 – the best players of the post-expansion era   = records = most nhl playoff games played by a goaltender (247) (third most playoff games of all players) most nhl playoff wins by a goaltender (151) first nhl goaltender to play 1,000 nhl games (finished with 1,029 games, later passed by martin brodeur) first nhl goaltender to win 500 games most conn smythe trophy wins — 3    awards    = as a player = calder cup — with the sherbrooke canadiens in 1985 stanley cup — with the montreal canadiens in 1986, 1993; with the colorado avalanche in 1996, 2001 conn smythe trophy — 1986, 1993, 2001 william m. jennings trophy — 1987*, 1988*, 1989*, 1992, 2002 vezina trophy — 1989, 1990, 1992 nhl all-star game — 1988, 1990, 1991, 1992, 1993, 1994, 1997, 1998, 2001, 2002, 2003 nhl first all-star team — 1989, 1990, 1992, 2002 nhl second all-star team — 1988, 1991 nhl all-rookie team — 1986 trico goaltending award — 1989, 1990 the colorado avalanche retired roy's number 33 jersey on october 28, 2003 the montreal canadiens retired roy's number 33 jersey on november 22, 2008 * shared with brian hayward   = as a coach = memorial cup — with quebec remparts in 2006 jack adams award — 2014    see also   list of nhl goaltenders with 300 wins list of nhl players with 1,000 games played    references     further reading  roy, michel (2010), patrick roy: winning, nothing else, wiley & sons canada, isbn 978-0-470-67944-9     external links  biographical information and career statistics from nhl.com, or eliteprospects.com, or hockey-reference.com, or legends of hockey, or the internet hockey database patrick roy biography at hockeygoalies.org - advanced statistics and game logs genealogy : patrick roy	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Patrick_Roy http://dbpedia.org/resource/Canada

ulugh beg was born in sultaniyeh in persia during timur's invasion.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ulugh_Beg http://dbpedia.org/resource/Sultan
marriages  ulugh beg had thirteen wives: aka begi begum, daughter of muhammad sultan mirza bin jahangir mirza and khan sultan khanika, mother of habiba sultan known as khanzada begum and another khanzada begum; sultan badi al-mulk begum, daughter of khalil sultan bin miran shah and shad malik agha; aqi sultan khanika, daughter of sultan mahmud khan ogeday; husn nigar khanika, daughter of shams-i-jahan khan chaghatay;  shukur bi khanika, daughter of darwish khan jochi; rukaiya sultan agha, an arlat lady, and mother of abdal-latif mirza, ak bash begum and sultan bakht begum; mihr sultan agha, daughter of tukal bin sarbuka; sa'adat bakht agha, daughter of bayan kukaltash, mother of qutlugh turkhan agha; daulat sultan agha, daughter of khawand sa'id; bakhti bi agha, daughter of aka sufi uzbek; daulat bakht agha, daughter of sheikh muhammad barlas; sultanim agha, mother of abdul hamid mirza and abdul jabrar mirza; sultan malik agha, daughter of nasir-al-din, mother of ubaydullah mirza, abdullah mirza and another abdullah mirza;    legacy  the crater, ulugh beigh, on the moon, was named after him by the german astronomer johann heinrich von mädler on his 1830 map of the moon.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ulugh_Beg http://dbpedia.org/resource/Sultan

clarice and lorenzo had 10 children, all except contessina antonia born in florence: lucrezia maria romola de' medici (1470–1553), who married jacopo salviati on 10 september 1486 and had 10 children of her own, including cardinal giovanni salviati, cardinal bernardo salviati, maria salviati (mother of cosimo i de' medici, grand duke of tuscany), and francesca salviati (mother of pope leo xi) twins who died after birth (march 1471) piero di lorenzo de' medici (1472–1503), called "the unfortunate", was ruler of florence after his father's death maria maddalena romola de' medici (1473–1528) married franceschetto cybo (illegitimate son of pope innocent viii) on 25 february 1487 and had seven children contessina beatrice de' medici, died shortly after her birth on 23 september 1474 giovanni di lorenzo de' medici (1475–1521), ascended to the papacy as leo x in 1513 luisa de' medici (1477–1488), also called luigia, was betrothed to giovanni de' medici il popolano, but died young contessina antonia romola de' medici (1478-1515), born in pistoia, married piero ridolfi (1467–1525) in 1494 and had five children, including cardinal niccolò ridolfi giuliano di lorenzo de' medici (1479–1516) was created duke of nemours in 1515 by king francis i of france lorenzo also adopted his nephew giulio, the illegitimate son of his slain brother giuliano.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lorenzo_de'_Medici http://dbpedia.org/resource/Florence
