horace appealed also to female poets, such as anna seward (original sonnets on various subjects, and odes paraphrased from horace, 1799) and elizabeth tollet, who composed a latin ode in sapphic meter to celebrate her brother's return from overseas, with tea and coffee substituted for the wine of horace's sympotic settings: horace's ars poetica is second only to aristotle's poetics in its influence on literary theory and criticism.	http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/gender http://dbpedia.org/resource/Horace male
quintus horatius flaccus (december 8, 65 bc – november 27, 8 bc), known in the english-speaking world as horace ( or ), was the leading roman lyric poet during the time of augustus (also known as octavian).	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Horace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
horace also crafted elegant hexameter verses (satires and epistles) and caustic iambic poetry (epodes).	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Horace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
some of the biographical writings contained in his writings can be supplemented from the short but valuable "life of horace" by suetonius (in his lives of the poets).	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Horace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
horace later claimed that he was reduced to poverty and this led him to try his hand at poetry.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Horace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
"as soon as horace, stirred by his own genius and encouraged by the example of virgil, varius, and perhaps some other poets of the same generation, had determined to make his fame as a poet, being by temperament a fighter, he wanted to fight against all kinds of prejudice, amateurish slovenliness, philistinism, reactionary tendencies, in short to fight for the new and noble type of poetry which he and his friends were endeavouring to bring about.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Horace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
horace generally followed the examples of poets established as classics in different genres, such as archilochus in the epodes, lucilius in the satires and alcaeus in the odes, later broadening his scope for the sake of variation and because his models weren't actually suited to the realities confronting him.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Horace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
horace proudly claimed to introduce into latin the spirit and iambic poetry of archilochus but (unlike archilochus) without persecuting anyone (epistles 1.19.23–5).	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Horace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
= themes = horace developed a number of inter-related themes throughout his poetic career, including politics, love, philosophy and ethics, his own social role, as well as poetry itself.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Horace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
many of horace's poems also contain much reflection on genre, the lyric tradition, and the function of poetry.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Horace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
in it, horace addresses the emperor augustus directly with more confidence and proclaims his power to grant poetic immortality to those he praises.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Horace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
in a verse epistle to augustus (epistle 2.1), in 12 bc, horace argued for classic status to be awarded to contemporary poets, including virgil and apparently himself.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Horace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
horace was often evoked by poets of the fourth century, such as ausonius and claudian.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Horace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
prudentius presented himself as a christian horace, adapting horatian meters to his own poetry and giving horatian motifs a christian tone.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Horace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
it can be argued that horace's influence extended beyond poetry to dignify core themes and values of the early christian era, such as self-sufficiency, inner contentment and courage.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Horace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
a twelfth century scholar encapsulated the theory: "...horace wrote four different kinds of poems on account of the four ages, the odes for boys, the ars poetica for young men, the satires for mature men, the epistles for old and complete men."	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Horace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
despite its naivety, the schematism involved an appreciation of horace's works as a collection, the ars poetica, satires and epistles appearing to find favour as well as the odes.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Horace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
in france, horace and pindar were the poetic models for a group of vernacular authors called the pléiade, including for example pierre de ronsard and joachim du bellay.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Horace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
ben jonson put horace on the stage in 1601 in poetaster, along with other classical latin authors, giving them all their own verses to speak in translation.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Horace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
it is not always easy to distinguish horace's influence during those centuries (the mixing of influences is shown for example in one poet's pseudonym, horace juvenal).	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Horace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
horace appealed also to female poets, such as anna seward (original sonnets on various subjects, and odes paraphrased from horace, 1799) and elizabeth tollet, who composed a latin ode in sapphic meter to celebrate her brother's return from overseas, with tea and coffee substituted for the wine of horace's sympotic settings: horace's ars poetica is second only to aristotle's poetics in its influence on literary theory and criticism.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Horace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
matthew arnold advised a friend in verse not to worry about politics, an echo of odes 2.11, yet later became a critic of horace's inadequacies relative to greek poets, as role models of victorian virtues, observing: "if human life were complete without faith, without enthusiasm, without energy, horace...would be the perfect interpreter of human life."	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Horace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
horace : behind the public poetry.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Horace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
horace and his lyric poetry.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Horace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet

life   molière was born in paris, the son of jean poquelin and marie cressé, the daughter of a prosperous bourgeois family.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Molière http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris
= return to paris = molière was forced to reach paris in stages, staying outside for a few weeks in order to promote himself with society gentlemen and allow his reputation to feed in to paris.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Molière http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris
les précieuses ridicules was the first of molière's many attempts to satirize certain societal mannerisms and affectations then common in france.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Molière http://dbpedia.org/resource/France
with some conjecture, molière's play can be seen to allude to the love affairs of louis xiv, then king of france.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Molière http://dbpedia.org/resource/France
molière's works continued to garner positive feedback in 18th-century england, but they were not so warmly welcomed in france at this time.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Molière http://dbpedia.org/resource/France
early life and rise to power (161–180)    = early life =  commodus was born on 31 august ad 161, as commodus, in lanuvium, near rome.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Commodus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rome
after those attempts on his life, commodus spent much of his time outside rome, mostly on the family estates at lanuvium.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Commodus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rome
perhaps seeing this as an opportunity, early in 192 commodus, declaring himself the new romulus, ritually re-founded rome, renaming the city colonia lucia annia commodiana.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Commodus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rome
commodus raised the ire of many military officials in rome for his hercules persona in the arena.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Commodus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rome

oskar schindler (28 april 1908 – 9 october 1974) was a german industrialist and a member of the nazi party, who is credited with saving the lives of 1,200 jews during the holocaust by employing them in his enamelware and ammunitions factories, which were located in occupied poland and the protectorate of bohemia and moravia.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Oskar_Schindler http://dbpedia.org/resource/Industrialist

valdas adamkus ([ˈvɐ̂ˑɫdɐs ɐˈdɐmˑkʊs] ( listen); born as voldemaras adamkavičius, 3 november 1926) is a lithuanian politician.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Valdas_Adamkus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lithuania
lithuanian presidency, 1998–2003  shortly after leaving the epa, valdas adamkus moved back to lithuania.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Valdas_Adamkus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lithuania
= domestic affairs = valdas adamkus enjoyed a very high approval rating in lithuania.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Valdas_Adamkus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lithuania
in his 2006 state of the nation address, adamkus stated that his top priorities were: increasing public participation in the political realm targeted and transparent use of the eu funds and opportunities for building a greater well-being in lithuania reforms in public governance, education and science, social support and health care the development of professional competence among civil servants, especially in assessing regulatory impacts approval of a political code of ethics direct mayoral elections, and elimination of the county system construction of a new nuclear power unit in ignalina legislation regulating the selection, appointment, and promotion of judges controlling "brain drain" by supporting research and higher education infrastructure    honours and awards  valdas adamkus has been honored with the following decorations:    honorary doctorates  valdas adamkus holds honorary doctorates at universities in lithuania, the united states and other countries, including: vilnius university, 1989.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Valdas_Adamkus http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lithuania

early life  beck was born in los angeles, to david campbell and bibbe hansen.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Beck http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles
beck began life in a rooming house near downtown los angeles.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Beck http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles
after his parents separated when he was ten, beck stayed with his mother and brother in los angeles, where he was influenced by the city's diverse musical offerings—everything from hip hop to latin music and his mother's art scene—all of which would later reappear in his recorded and published work.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Beck http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles
daunted by the prospect of another homeless new york winter, beck returned to his home of los angeles in early 1991.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Beck http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles

that night, beck performed at the los angeles club cafe troy to a packed audience and talent scouts from major labels.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Beck http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles

early life   prince salim, later jahangir, was born on august 31, 1569, in fatehpur sikri, to akbar and jodha bai.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/parent http://dbpedia.org/resource/Jahangir http://dbpedia.org/resource/Akbar
conquests  in the year 1594, jahangir was dispatched by his father, the mughal emperor akbar, alongside abul hasan asaf khan, also known as mirza jaafar beg son of mirza ghias beg isfahani and brother of nur jehan, and abu'l-fazl ibn mubarak, to defeat the renegade vir singh deo of bundela and capture the city of orchha, which was considered the centre of the revolt.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/parent http://dbpedia.org/resource/Jahangir http://dbpedia.org/resource/Akbar
jahangir also thought of capturing kangra fort, which akbar had failed to do in 1615.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/parent http://dbpedia.org/resource/Jahangir http://dbpedia.org/resource/Akbar
sir william hawkins who visited jahangir's court in 1609, said: "in such short that what this man's father, called ecber padasha [padshah akbar], got of the deccans, this king, selim sha [jahangir] beginneth to lose."	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/parent http://dbpedia.org/resource/Jahangir http://dbpedia.org/resource/Akbar
jahangir married the extremely beautiful and intelligent mehr-un-nisaa (better known by her subsequent title of nur jahan) on may 25, 1611.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/Jahangir http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nur_Jahan
jahangir married her in 1611 and gave her the title of nur jahan or "light of the world".	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/Jahangir http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nur_Jahan

sami frashëri (turkish: şemseddin sami, june 1, 1850 – june 18, 1904) was an ottoman albanian writer, philosopher, playwright and a prominent figure of the rilindja kombëtare, the national renaissance movement of albania, together with his two brothers abdyl and naim.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Sami_Frashëri http://dbpedia.org/resource/Albania
life   sami frashëri was born in 1850 in the village of frashër in the vilayet of janina to a distinguished muslim albanian family of bektashi religious affiliations.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Sami_Frashëri http://dbpedia.org/resource/Albania
sami frashëri also founded and headed in istanbul the society for the publication of albanian writings in october 1879, where albanian scholastic books and texts were compiled by him and his brother naim.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Sami_Frashëri http://dbpedia.org/resource/Albania
sami frashëri together with jani vreto supported the idea that the albanian alphabet should be based on the greek alphabet, since according to them, albanians and greeks have the same ancestors, the pelasgians.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Sami_Frashëri http://dbpedia.org/resource/Albania

nikhil kumar (born 15 july 1941) is an indian politician who was governor of nagaland from 2009 to 2013 and governor of kerala from 2013 to 2014.one of country's well knownips officers of 1963 batch, kumar also served as chief of the national security guards, indo-tibetan border police and as commissioner of delhi police.he was elected member of the 14th lok sabha of india, representing the aurangabad constituency in bihar as a member of the indian national congress (inc) political party.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nikhil_Kumar http://dbpedia.org/resource/India

paul michael levesque (born july 27, 1969), better known by the ring name triple h (an abbreviation of his original wwe ring name hunter hearst helmsley), is an american business executive, professional wrestler, and actor.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Triple_H http://dbpedia.org/resource/WWE
on the june 6, 2002 episode of smackdown!, triple h defeated hogan in a #1 contender match for the undisputed wwe championship at the king of the ring against the undertaker, but was unsuccessful at the event.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Triple_H http://dbpedia.org/resource/WWE
after vengeance, triple h took a hiatus from wwe due to suffering from minor neck problems.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Triple_H http://dbpedia.org/resource/WWE
after four-month hiatus, triple h returned to raw on october 3, 2005 as part of wwe homecoming.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Triple_H http://dbpedia.org/resource/WWE
later that month at backlash, triple h was involved in another wwe championship match, fighting edge and cena in a triple threat match, where he lost again.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Triple_H http://dbpedia.org/resource/WWE
triple h unsuccessfully attempted to win the wwe title from cena on numerous occasions, blaming his shortcomings on vince mcmahon, which eventually led to a feud between the mcmahons and triple h. shawn michaels returned on the june 12 episode of raw and soon reunited with triple h to re-form d-generation x, turning triple h into a fan favorite once again for the first time since 2002.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Triple_H http://dbpedia.org/resource/WWE
however, at the start of the night, triple h decided to challenge newly named wwe champion randy orton, reigniting his rivalry with orton that had been interrupted following his injury.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Triple_H http://dbpedia.org/resource/WWE
triple h won the match, winning his eleventh world championship and sixth wwe championship, and then defended his title against umaga in his regularly scheduled match after mr. mcmahon declared the match to be for the wwe title.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Triple_H http://dbpedia.org/resource/WWE
triple h's title reign at no mercy is the fifth shortest reign in wwe history, only lasting through the duration of the event.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Triple_H http://dbpedia.org/resource/WWE
triple h then went on to defeat cleanly john cena to successfully defend the wwe championship at night of champions.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Triple_H http://dbpedia.org/resource/WWE
on the june 23 episode of raw, triple h was drafted to the smackdown brand as a part of the 2008 wwe draft, in the process making the wwe championship exclusive to smackdown.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Triple_H http://dbpedia.org/resource/WWE
triple h made an untelevised appearance on october 30 at the wwe fan appreciation event and also at the 2010 tribute to the troops.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Triple_H http://dbpedia.org/resource/WWE
at the end of the july 18 episode of raw, triple h returned on behalf of wwe's board of directors to relieve his father-in-law vince mcmahon of his duties.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Triple_H http://dbpedia.org/resource/WWE
upon his return two weeks later, triple h was confronted by lesnar's legal representative, paul heyman, who announced lesnar was filing a lawsuit against wwe for breach of contract.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Triple_H http://dbpedia.org/resource/WWE
the authority (2013–2016)   on the august 12 episode of raw, triple h announced that he would be the special guest referee of the summerslam main event: the wwe championship match between champion john cena and daniel bryan before attacking brad maddox with a pedigree.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Triple_H http://dbpedia.org/resource/WWE
on the june 2 episode of raw, batista would leave the group after triple h refused to grant him his shot at the wwe world heavyweight championship.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Triple_H http://dbpedia.org/resource/WWE
triple h returned at the 2016 royal rumble match for the wwe world heavyweight championship, as the unannounced 30th entrant.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Triple_H http://dbpedia.org/resource/WWE
after wrestlemania 32, with the authority now disbanded, triple h competed in the wwe live tour of the united kingdom in late april before taking a hiatus from wwe television, whilst occasionally appearing at nxt and cruiserweight classic events.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Triple_H http://dbpedia.org/resource/WWE
various appearances (2016–present)  on the august 29 episode of raw, triple h made his return by interfering in the main event for the recently vacated and established wwe universal championship.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Triple_H http://dbpedia.org/resource/WWE
the following week, angle revealed that although triple h and stephanie were wwe executives, they also had contracts to compete as wrestlers.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Triple_H http://dbpedia.org/resource/WWE

the list of rembrandt pupils from his period in leiden as well as his time in amsterdam is quite long, mostly because his influence on painters around him was so great that it is difficult to tell whether someone worked for him in his studio or just copied his style for patrons eager to acquire a rembrandt.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rembrandt http://dbpedia.org/resource/Leiden

life    = early life and education =  france prešeren was born in the upper carniolan village of vrba, then part of the habsburg monarchy (today in slovenia), as the third of eight children and the first son in the family of a well-off farmer and an ambitious and better educated mother who taught her children to write and read and soon sent them to their uncles who were roman catholic priests.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/France_Prešeren http://dbpedia.org/resource/Habsburg_Monarchy

notable chess games  tigran petrosian vs vasily smyslov, ussr championship, moscow 1949, sicilian defence, scheveningen variation (b84), 0–1 the first meeting of two future world champions goes to smyslov in a precise positional performance.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Vasily_Smyslov http://dbpedia.org/resource/Moscow
vasily smyslov vs efim geller, ussr championship, moscow 1951, sicilian defence, closed variation (b26), 1–0 smyslov used the closed sicilian periodically throughout his life, and made many important improvements.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Vasily_Smyslov http://dbpedia.org/resource/Moscow
vasily smyslov vs mikhail botvinnik, world championship match, moscow 1954, game 9, french defence, winawer variation (c17), 1–0 smyslov blows up one of the world champion's favourite variations with a queen sacrifice to score a stunning win.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Vasily_Smyslov http://dbpedia.org/resource/Moscow
mikhail botvinnik vs vasily smyslov, world championship match, moscow 1954, game 14, king's indian defence, fianchetto variation (e68), 0–1 with one of the deepest pre-game home preparations ever seen, smyslov unleashes a chain of tactical wizardry, including a queen sacrifice, to record a beautiful win which fundamentally changed the theory in this variation.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Vasily_Smyslov http://dbpedia.org/resource/Moscow
vasily smyslov vs boris spassky, moscow vs leningrad team match 1960, alekhine's defence (b05), 1–0 spassky tries the unusual alekhine's defence and is beaten in fairly short order.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Vasily_Smyslov http://dbpedia.org/resource/Moscow

jean-claude duvalier (french pronunciation: ​[ʒɑ̃klod dyvalje]), nicknamed “baby doc” (haitian creole: bebe dòk) (3 july 1951 – 4 october 2014), was the president of haiti from 1971 until he was overthrown by a popular uprising in 1986.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Jean-Claude_Duvalier http://dbpedia.org/resource/Haiti
initially, jean-claude duvalier resisted the dynastic arrangement that had made him haiti's leader, having preferred that the presidency go to his older sister marie-denise duvalier, and was content to leave substantive and administrative matters in the hands of his mother, simone ovide duvalier, and a committee led by luckner cambronne, his father's interior minister, while he attended ceremonial functions and lived as a playboy.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Jean-Claude_Duvalier http://dbpedia.org/resource/Haiti

until finally humayun had gathered hundreds of sindhi and baloch tribesmen alongside his mughals and then marched towards kandahar and later kabul, thousands more gathered by his side as humayun continually declared himself the rightful timurid heir of the first mughal emperor, babur.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Humayun http://dbpedia.org/resource/Kabul
humayun now prepared to take kabul, ruled by his brother kamran mirza.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Humayun http://dbpedia.org/resource/Kabul
early reign   when humayun came to the throne of the mughal empire, several of his brothers revolted against him.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Humayun http://dbpedia.org/resource/Mughal_Empire
humayun refused, citing the last words of his father, babur, "do nothing against your brothers, even though they may deserve it."	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/parent http://dbpedia.org/resource/Humayun http://dbpedia.org/resource/Babur
emir hussein umrani, ruler of sindh, welcomed humayun's presence and was loyal to humayun just as he had been loyal to babur against the renegade arghuns.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/parent http://dbpedia.org/resource/Humayun http://dbpedia.org/resource/Babur
on 23 july 1555, humayun once again sat on babur's throne in delhi.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/parent http://dbpedia.org/resource/Humayun http://dbpedia.org/resource/Babur
some believe that before falling from the staircase once humayun was very ill and to save him his father (babur) performed a practice known as sadgah by which he gave his life to humayun who was about to die.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/parent http://dbpedia.org/resource/Humayun http://dbpedia.org/resource/Babur

literary career  unlike most representatives of the so-called “new wave” of russian-american writing, maxim d. shrayer had written and published extensively in his native russian prior to having made a transition to writing prose predominantly in english.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Maxim_D._Shrayer http://dbpedia.org/resource/Russia

şehzade mehmed (1605, constantinople, topkapı palace – murdered by osman ii, 12 january 1621, istanbul, topkapı palace, buried in ahmed i mausoleum, sultan ahmed mosque) with mahfiruz; or kosem; şehzade orhan (1610 constantinople, topkapı palace – murdered 1 june 1622 topkapı palace buried in ahmed i mausoleum, sultan ahmed mosque) sultan murad iv (27 july 1612, constantinople – 8 february 1640, constantinople, topkapı palace, buried in ahmed i mausoleum, sultan ahmed mosque), with kösem, sultan of the ottoman empire; ahmad kasravi (29 september 1890 – 11 march 1946; persian: احمد کسروی‎) was a notable iranian linguist, historian, nationalist and reformer.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ahmad_Kasravi http://dbpedia.org/resource/Iran
arguing that the ancient azari language had been closely related to persian language and the influx of turkic words began only with the seljuq invasion, ahmad kasravi believed that the true national language of iranian azerbaijan was persian and therefore advocated the linguistic assimilation of persian in azarbaijan.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ahmad_Kasravi http://dbpedia.org/resource/Iran
isbn 978-1-86064-552-5 ahmad kasravi, tārikh-e mashruteh-ye iran (history of the iranian constitutional revolution), in persian, 951 p. (negāh publications, tehran, 2003), isbn 964-351-138-3.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ahmad_Kasravi http://dbpedia.org/resource/Iran

(mazda publications, costa mesa, california, 2006).	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ahmad_Kasravi http://dbpedia.org/resource/Iran

ultimately, nichiren drew the anger of japan's ruling hōjō clan when his two lotus sutra-based predictions of foreign invasion and political strife were seemingly actualized by the mongol invasions of japan and an attempted coup within the hōjō clan.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nichiren http://dbpedia.org/resource/Japan
to eliminate any possible doubts, nichiren decided to spend some time at mount kōya, the centre of shingon buddhism, and also in nara, japan's ancient capital, where he studied the risshū, which emphasized strict adherence to the vinaya, the code of monastic discipline and ordination.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nichiren http://dbpedia.org/resource/Japan

nichiren thought this could be achieved in japan by withdrawing lay support so that the other monks which he viewed as corrupt would be forced to change their ways or revert to laymen to prevent starving.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nichiren http://dbpedia.org/resource/Japan

early life and career  đỗ mười was born on 2 february 1917 in dong phu, thanh trì, hanoi as nguyễn duy cống and was the son of nguyen xeng.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Đỗ_Mười http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hanoi
during the late 1970s, đỗ mười oversaw the socialisation of the south vietnamese economy.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Đỗ_Mười http://dbpedia.org/resource/Vietnam
during the 1980s đỗ mười began to believe that economic reforms were necessary to improve the vietnamese economy, however, he still subscribed to the view that the planned economy was better adapted to developing economies than a market economy.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Đỗ_Mười http://dbpedia.org/resource/Vietnam
đỗ mười joined the communist party of vietnam in 1939, but was arrested by french authorities in 1941 or 1942 and was sentenced for 10 years to forced labour at the hoa lo prison.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Đỗ_Mười http://dbpedia.org/resource/Vietnam
on 31 march 1978 đỗ mười signed a decree, on the behalf of prime minister phạm văn đông, on forbidding private property in vietnam.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Đỗ_Mười http://dbpedia.org/resource/Vietnam
by 1984 đỗ mười was subscribing to the view that the vietnamese economic system needed to be reformed; his original plan was to reform the price and wage system and to abolish subsidies for state enterprises.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Đỗ_Mười http://dbpedia.org/resource/Vietnam
at the 10th plenum of the 6th central committee (held september 1990), đỗ mười's report to the plenum stressed the substantial drop of soviet and eastern bloc assistance levels to vietnam, the concurrent increase in imports, the level of national debt and "natural calamities" in agriculture.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Đỗ_Mười http://dbpedia.org/resource/Vietnam
in his plans for 1991, đỗ mười sought to: develop export markets and draw increased foreign investments to vietnam and to obtain foreign technology; eliminate state subsidies in production, business and capital construction; rationalise state policies by privatising inefficient state-run enterprises; encourage family-based economic units; and undertake regional development, creating employment and reducing unemployment.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Đỗ_Mười http://dbpedia.org/resource/Vietnam
longevity  at the age of 101 years, 57 days đỗ mười is the oldest living and earliest serving former general secretary of the communist party of vietnam.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Đỗ_Mười http://dbpedia.org/resource/Vietnam
đỗ mười is the second oldest vietnamese communist figure by age after võ nguyên giáp who lived to 102 years, 40 days.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Đỗ_Mười http://dbpedia.org/resource/Vietnam

malietoa tanumafili ii  (4 january 1913 – 11 may 2007), also called susuga, was the malietoa, the title of one of samoa's four paramount chiefs, and the head of state, or o le ao o le malo, a position that he held for life, of samoa from 1962 to 2007.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Malietoa_Tanumafili_II http://dbpedia.org/resource/Samoa
death  malietoa tanumafili ii died at 18:45 on friday 11 may 2007, at the tupua tamasese meaole national hospital at moto'otua in apia, samoa.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Malietoa_Tanumafili_II http://dbpedia.org/resource/Samoa
= international reaction =  united kingdom – queen elizabeth ii stated: "i have learned with great sadness of the death of his highness malietoa tanumafili ii, i recall with pleasure my visit to samoa, with prince philip, in 1977.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Malietoa_Tanumafili_II http://dbpedia.org/resource/Samoa
micronesia – newly elected micronesian president manny mori sent a letter to samoan prime minister tuila'epa sailele malielegaoi stating that malietoa tanumafili ii was a "great leader and pioneer of samoa...as a great leader of the independent state of samoa, his highness malietoa tanumafili ii was one of the prominent samoan leaders leading up to its independence in 1962...his wisdom, leadership and dedication contributed to the forgoing and eventual inception of the samoan nation...our thoughts and prayers are with you during this time of national mourning."	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Malietoa_Tanumafili_II http://dbpedia.org/resource/Samoa

biography    = early life and world war ii = mohammad asghar khan was born in jammu, jammu and kashmir in british indian empire on 17 january 1921.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Asghar_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/British_Indian_Empire
biography    = early life and world war ii = mohammad asghar khan was born in jammu, jammu and kashmir in british indian empire on 17 january 1921.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Asghar_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Kashmir
biography    = early life and world war ii = mohammad asghar khan was born in jammu, jammu and kashmir in british indian empire on 17 january 1921.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Asghar_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Jammu
air marshal asghar khan (urdu: ائیر مارشل اصغر خان‬‎; 17 january 1921 – 5 january 2018) was pakistani politician, aviation historian, peace activist, and retired three star rank air force general who served as the first native commander in chief of the pakistan air force (paf) under president iskander mirza (1956–59) and under president ayub khan until resigning in 1965 prior to the start of the air operations of the paf during the indo-pakistani war of 1965.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Asghar_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pakistan
upon return to british indian empire, asghar khan resumed his active duty with the royal indian air force and opted for pakistan following the independence in 1947, and settled in west-pakistan.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Asghar_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pakistan
asghar khan became first commandant of pakistan air force academy in 1947 and was also the first to head the directorate-general for air operations (dgao) in 1950.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Asghar_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pakistan
after retiring from air force, asghar khan became president of civilian national flag carrier, the pakistan international airlines (pia) which he led until 1968.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Asghar_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pakistan
after years of founding the independence movement, asghar khan merged his party with pakistan tehreek-e-insaf, led by cricketer-turned politician imran khan, in january 2012.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Asghar_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pakistan
asghar khan and all his brothers, except his youngest brother, joined the armed forces of pakistan, after the family relocated to abbottabad during partition.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Asghar_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pakistan
in 1948, asghar khan greeted founder of pakistan and governor-general muhammad ali jinnah when jinnah visited the pakistan air force academy.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Asghar_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pakistan
= commander-in-chief =  after the retirement of air vice-marshal (avm) arthur mcdonald, prime minister huseyn suhravardy approved the appointment of asghar khan as the commander-in-chief of pakistan air force.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Asghar_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pakistan
in protest, asghar khan relinquished awards of 'hilal-i-pakistan' and 'hilal-i-quaid-i-azam' as a protest against repressive policies of field marshal ayub khan in january 1969.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Asghar_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pakistan
during the bangladesh liberation war, asghar khan did support the east-pakistan morally, alleging the west-pakistan under bhutto, of depriving east from their political and economical rights.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Asghar_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pakistan
during the 1977 elections, asghar khan allied his party, the tehreek-i-istiqlal with the pakistan national alliance (pna) against the people's party.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Asghar_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pakistan
all of these members left asghar khan under navaz sharif who founded the largest conservative party, the pakistan muslim league (n).	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Asghar_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pakistan
in a historic press conference on 12 december 2011, asghar khan announced his full support to pakistan tehreek-e-insaf (pti) and imran khan.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Asghar_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pakistan
on various occasion, asghar khan called for normalization of indo-pakistan relations.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Asghar_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pakistan
asghar khan also renounced the nuclear tests operations conducted by pakistan, targeting prime minister nawaz sharif move for making that move.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Asghar_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pakistan
in 2011 asghar khan maintained that:  in the last over 60 years, india has never attacked pakistan, as it cannot afford it.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Asghar_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pakistan
moreover, again at kargil, indian never mounted an assault...  asghar khan blamed zulfikar ali bhutto for balochistan conflict and the east-pakistan war, terming it "inflexible attitude" of bhutto.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Asghar_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pakistan
commenting of his political collapse, asghar khan accused the civil society for his failure, and marked that: " the majority in pakistan voted for the (corrupt) politicians, as they also wanted their job done by "hook or by crook".	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Asghar_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pakistan
during the bangladesh liberation war, asghar khan did support the east-pakistan morally, alleging the west pakistan under bhutto, of depriving east pakistan from their political and economical rights.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Asghar_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pakistan
am (rtd) asghar khan had once filed a petition with the supreme court of pakistan in 1996.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Asghar_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pakistan
the said asghar khan case [challenging unlawful distribution of rs:140 million amongst ‘some chosen’ politicians by the pakistan army’s isi in 1990’s parliamentary elections] caught momentum when the apex court was moved once again in december 2011 [may be just by coincidence] on the basis of an article ‘similar looks wanted please’, appeared on internet media through www.pkhope.com on 8 october 2011.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Asghar_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pakistan
asghar khan has also authored 13 books, including we've learnt nothing from history, pakistan at the crossroads and generals in politics.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Asghar_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pakistan
initially commissioned in the indian army, asghar khan was drafted into indian air force in 1940, seeing actions in burma campaign and was later sent to united kingdom where he graduated from raf staff college at bracknell, completing his collegiate courses from joint service defence college, and completed his post-graduate studies from imperial defence college.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Asghar_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/United_Kingdom
after world war ii, asghar khan was sent to united kingdom where he joined the raf staff college at bracknell, where he completed a staff course.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/country http://dbpedia.org/resource/Asghar_Khan http://dbpedia.org/resource/United_Kingdom

& c. boni), )1929) american poets, 1630-1930 (little, brown), (1932) american and british literature since 1890 (1939), with carl van doren shakespeare (1939) the liberal education (1943) the night of the summer solstice: & other stories of the russian war, (henry holt and company), (1943) the noble voice (1946) nathaniel hawthorne (1949) introduction to poetry (1951) the autobiography of mark van doren (1958) the happy critic (1961) mark van doren on great poems of western literature.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Mark_Van_Doren http://dbpedia.org/resource/Critic
mark van doren went on to become one of columbia's greatest teachers and a "legendary classroom presence"; he became a full professor in 1942, and taught english until 1959, at which point he became professor emeritus until his death in 1972  his students at columbia included the poets and writers john berryman, allen ginsberg, jack kerouac, louis simpson, richard howard, lionel trilling (later a colleague), robert lax, anthony robinson, as well as the japanologist and interpreter of japanese literature donald keene, author and activist whittaker chambers, writer and trappist monk thomas merton, walter b. pitkin jr and poet-critic john hollander.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Mark_Van_Doren http://dbpedia.org/resource/Teacher

in 2001 she was the winner of pearl s. buck award   = former positions = egypt's first lady from 1970 to 1981 first woman chair of the people's council of munofeyya provincial governorate visiting professor at american university, university of south carolina, and radford university in the united states    references     external links  madame jehan sadat official website biography at the anwar sadat chair for peace and development at the university of maryland biography at women's international center appearances on c-span jehan sadat on charlie rose jehan sadat on imdb works by or about jehan sadat in libraries (worldcat catalog) thirty years later, sadat's widow still hopes for peace, cnn, 26 march 2009	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/Jehan_Sadat http://dbpedia.org/resource/Anwar_Sadat

family de graeff  andries de graeff was born in amsterdam, the third son of jacob dircksz de graeff and aaltje boelens loen.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Andries_de_Graeff http://dbpedia.org/resource/Amsterdam
het vers op den edelen en gestrengen heer andries de graeff, ouden raet en rekenmeester der graeflijckheit van hollant, en west-vrieslant, nu out-burgermeester, en zeeraedt t'amsterdam at his city palace in the gouden bocht ("golden bend"), the most prestigious part of herengracht, he assembled a big art collection, including jacob blessing the sons of joseph of rembrandt.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Andries_de_Graeff http://dbpedia.org/resource/Amsterdam

political career  andries de graeff was from 1646 a member of the vroedschap and from 1657-71 mayor seven times in the difficult times of the first stadtholderless period.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Andries_de_Graeff http://dbpedia.org/resource/Mayor

fan zhongyan (5 september 989 – 19 june 1052) from wu county of suzhou (jiangsu province, china), courtesy name xiwen (希文), ratified as the duke of wenzheng (文正公) posthumously, and conferred as duke of chu (楚國公) posthumously, is one of the most prominent figures in the chinese history, as a founder of neo-confucianism and a great statesman, philosopher, writer, educator, military strategist, and philanthropist.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Fan_Zhongyan http://dbpedia.org/resource/Suzhou

sheikh abdullah was introduced to jawaharlal nehru in 1937 and as he too was a leader of the indian national congress was demanding similar rights for people of british india and had formed the all india states peoples conference for supporting the people of princely states in their struggle for a representative government the two became friends and political allies.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Sheikh_Abdullah http://dbpedia.org/resource/India
this, sheikh abdullah hoped, would take over the defence of kashmir after the indian army was withdrawn.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Sheikh_Abdullah http://dbpedia.org/resource/India
nehru requested sheikh abdullah to act as a bridge between india and pakistan and make president ayub to agree to come to new delhi for talks for a final solution of the kashmir problem.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Sheikh_Abdullah http://dbpedia.org/resource/India

policy towards missionaries   in february 1825, minh mạng banned missionaries from entering vietnam.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Minh_Mạng http://dbpedia.org/resource/Vietnam
= conquests and ethnic minority policy =  minh mạng enacted the final conquest of the champa kingdom after the centuries long cham–vietnamese wars.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Minh_Mạng http://dbpedia.org/resource/Vietnam
minh mạng sinicized ethnic minorities such as cambodians, claimed the legacy of confucianism and china's han dynasty for vietnam, and used the term han people 漢人 (hán nhân) to refer to the vietnamese.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Minh_Mạng http://dbpedia.org/resource/Vietnam
minh mạng implemented an acculturation integration policy directed at minority non-vietnamese peoples.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Minh_Mạng http://dbpedia.org/resource/Vietnam
minh mạng pursued a policy of cultural assimilation of non-viet ethnic groups which from 1841, through 1845, led to southern vietnam experiencing a series of ethnic revolts.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Minh_Mạng http://dbpedia.org/resource/Vietnam
early years  born nguyễn phúc đảm at gia định in the middle of the second tây sơn - nguyễn civil war, minh mạng was the fourth son of lord nguyễn phúc ánh - future emperor gia long.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/parent http://dbpedia.org/resource/Minh_Mạng http://dbpedia.org/resource/Emperor
when minh mạng died, he left the throne to his son, emperor thiệu trị, who was more rigidly confucianist and anti-imperialist than his father.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/parent http://dbpedia.org/resource/Minh_Mạng http://dbpedia.org/resource/Emperor

howard hughes medical institute   in 1953, hughes launched the howard hughes medical institute in miami, florida (currently located in chevy chase, maryland) with the expressed goal of basic biomedical research, including trying to understand, in hughes' words, the "genesis of life itself," due to his lifelong interest in science and technology.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Howard_Hughes http://dbpedia.org/resource/Howard_Hughes_Medical_Institute

zewditu had two further marriages, both brief, before marrying ras gugsa welle.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/Zewditu http://dbpedia.org/resource/Gugsa_Welle
unlike her prior marriages, zewditu's marriage to gugsa welle is thought to have been happy.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/Zewditu http://dbpedia.org/resource/Gugsa_Welle
in an attempt to limit her influence, the aristocracy arranged for her nephew—zewditu's husband ras gugsa welle—to be appointed to a remote governorship, removing him from court.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/Zewditu http://dbpedia.org/resource/Gugsa_Welle
in 1930, zewditu's husband ras gugsa welle led a rebellion against negus tafari in begemder, hoping to end the regency in spite of his wife's repeated pleas and orders to desist, but was defeated and killed in battle by the modernised ethiopian army at the battle of anchem on 31 march 1930.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/Zewditu http://dbpedia.org/resource/Gugsa_Welle
in 1886 the ten-year-old zewditu was married to ras araya selassie yohannes, son and heir of emperor yohannes iv.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/spouse http://dbpedia.org/resource/Zewditu http://dbpedia.org/resource/Araya_Selassie_Yohannes

in 929, li siyuan made li conghou the military governor of hedong and the defender of taiyuan, while making li congrong the mayor of henan and the commander of the imperial guards.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Li_Conghou http://dbpedia.org/resource/Taiyuan
background  li conghou was born in 914, when his father li siyuan was a general of jin (predecessor state to later tang), under his adoptive brother (li conghou's adoptive uncle) li cunxu the prince of jin.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/parent http://dbpedia.org/resource/Li_Conghou http://dbpedia.org/resource/Li_Siyuan
meanwhile, it was said that li conghou developed a reputation for being respectful, humble, and willing to listen to others — characteristics that li siyuan hoped that his older brother li congrong, who was then the military governor of hedong circuit (河東, headquartered at taiyuan) would emulate (as li congrong was said to be arrogant and violent), to no avail.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/parent http://dbpedia.org/resource/Li_Conghou http://dbpedia.org/resource/Li_Siyuan
li siyuan subsequently decided to summon li conghou, but before li conghou could arrive at luoyang, li siyuan died.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/parent http://dbpedia.org/resource/Li_Conghou http://dbpedia.org/resource/Li_Siyuan
li conghou was buried with only ceremony due a prince, south of li siyuan's tomb.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/parent http://dbpedia.org/resource/Li_Conghou http://dbpedia.org/resource/Li_Siyuan

youth  eugen filotti was born in bucharest, romania.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Eugen_Filotti http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romania
in his own articles on the exhibition, eugen filotti presented the event in a positive light, and highlighted the value of the work exposed by romanian artists, stressing that they were in no way inferior to the foreign participants.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Eugen_Filotti http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romania
after being appointed press attaché in prague where he worked for over a year, in 1928 eugen filotti was transferred to the romanian mission to the league of nations in geneva.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Eugen_Filotti http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romania
în his capacity of director of the press, eugen filotti had the responsibility of verifying the activity of foreign press correspondents working in romania.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Eugen_Filotti http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romania
eugen filotti was able to point these malversations and, at last, julius köver was expelled from romania.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Eugen_Filotti http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romania
apart from his activities in the ministry of foreign affairs, after returning from his missions in prague and in geneva, eugen filotti renewed his contacts with the romanian cultural elite.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Eugen_Filotti http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romania
eugen filotti's diplomatic experience was an important element in defining the position of the romanian delegation at the dubrovnik congress.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Eugen_Filotti http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romania
eugen filotti made important efforts to strengthen the romanian high school in thessaloniki and to extend the network of romanian primary schools which had been established in the villages of epirus, thessaly, west and central macedonia with high concentrations of aromanian population.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Eugen_Filotti http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romania
the problems of minorities were an important to the bilateral romano-bulgarian diplomatic relations and it was inevitable that, in his new position, eugen filotti would be confronted with issues related the rights of the romanian minority in bulgaria.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Eugen_Filotti http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romania
as he had done in athens, eugen filotti concentrated his efforts on strengthening the romanian education network in bulgaria, which included primary schools in the villages with romanian population along the danube as well as a romanian high school in sofia.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Eugen_Filotti http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romania
eugen filotti was appointed the new romanian minister plenipotentiary to budapest.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Eugen_Filotti http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romania
even before eugen filotti's arrival in budapest, the government of romania had forwarded complaints to berlin and to rome, following which the roggieri-altenburg commission was created to investigate the accusations brought either by romania or by hungary and to recommend corrective actions.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Eugen_Filotti http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romania
another active factor in this set-up was nicolae bălan, metropolite of transylvania, whom eugen filotti met in sibiu each time he returned to romania, in order to coordinate the actions taken on religious and diplomatic channels.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Eugen_Filotti http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romania
these informations were relayed to the romanian legation in budapest, and, in his capacity of plenipotentiary minister, eugen filotti visited these places to gain first hand information on how the romanians were treated.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Eugen_Filotti http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romania
at the same time, eugen filotti got actively involved with the diplomats who were preparing the coup which would take romania out of the alliance with germany, and make the country switch sides to join the allies.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Eugen_Filotti http://dbpedia.org/resource/Romania
youth  eugen filotti was born in bucharest, romania.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Eugen_Filotti http://dbpedia.org/resource/Bucharest
in 1902–1906 eugen filotti attended the cuibul cu barză school, on ştirbei vodă street, in bucharest and thereafter, from 1906 to 1914 gheorghe lazăr high school in bucharest.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Eugen_Filotti http://dbpedia.org/resource/Bucharest
after having concluded his lead role in the negotiations with bulgaria, eugen filotti was recalled to bucharest.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Eugen_Filotti http://dbpedia.org/resource/Bucharest
the dioceses would then forward the pertinent information to eugen filotti, at the legation in budapest, from where it was sent through diplomatic channels to bucharest.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Eugen_Filotti http://dbpedia.org/resource/Bucharest
after reviewing it, eugen filotti chose to short circuit the ministry of foreign affairs in bucharest, and, in order to make sure that it became known to the international community, send it directly to vespasian pella, the romanian minister plenipotentiary in bern, who presented it to the international committee of the red cross in geneva.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Eugen_Filotti http://dbpedia.org/resource/Bucharest

pierre de ronsard (11 september 1524 – 27 december 1585) was a french poet or, as his own generation in france called him, a "prince of poets".	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pierre_de_Ronsard http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
voltaire, pretending to work in paris as an assistant to a notary, spent much of his time writing poetry.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Voltaire http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris
most of voltaire's early life revolved around paris.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Voltaire http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris
after voltaire's recovery from a month-long smallpox infection in november 1723, the first copies were smuggled into paris and distributed.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Voltaire http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris
after two and a half years in exile, voltaire returned to france, and after a few months living in dieppe, the authorities permitted him to return to paris.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Voltaire http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris
= prussia =  after the death of the marquise in childbirth in september 1749, voltaire briefly returned to paris and in mid-1750 moved to prussia to the court of frederick the great.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Voltaire http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris
= geneva and ferney =  voltaire's slow progress toward paris continued through mainz, mannheim, strasbourg, and colmar, but in january 1754 louis xv banned him from paris, so instead he turned for geneva, near which he bought a large estate (les délices) in early 1755.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Voltaire http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris
on 4 april 1778 voltaire accompanied his close friend benjamin franklin into la loge des neuf sœurs or les neuf sœurs in paris, france and became an entered apprentice freemason.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Voltaire http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris
= death and burial = in february 1778, voltaire returned for the first time in over 25 years to paris, among other reasons to see the opening of his latest tragedy, irene.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Voltaire http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris
because of his well-known criticism of the church, which he had refused to retract before his death, voltaire was denied a christian burial in paris, but friends and relations managed to bury his body secretly at the abbey of scellières in champagne, where marie louise's brother was abbé.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Voltaire http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris
in his lettres sur la nouvelle heloise, written under a pseudonym, voltaire offered criticism highlighting grammatical mistakes in the book:  paris recognized voltaire's hand and judged the patriarch to be bitten by jealousy.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Voltaire http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris
rené pomeau, la religion de voltaire, librairie nizet, paris, 1974.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Voltaire http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris
voltaire's own book eléments de la philosophie de newton (elements of newton's philosophy) made newton accessible and understandable to a far greater public, and the marquise wrote a celebratory review in the journal des savants.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Voltaire http://dbpedia.org/resource/Philosophy
voltaire and the marquise also explored philosophy, particularly metaphysics, the branch of philosophy that deals with being and with what lies beyond the material realm, such as whether or not there is a god and whether people have souls.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Voltaire http://dbpedia.org/resource/Philosophy

hedd wyn (born ellis humphrey evans, 13 january 1887 – 31 july 1917) was a welsh-language poet who was killed on the first day of the battle of passchendaele during world war i.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hedd_Wyn http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
hedd wyn's main influence was the romantic poetry of percy bysshe shelley and themes of nature and religion dominated his work.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hedd_Wyn http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
the war inspired hedd wyn's work and produced some of his most noted poetry, including plant trawsfynydd ("children of trawsfynydd"), y blotyn du ("the black dot"), and nid â’n ango ("[it] will not be forgotten").	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hedd_Wyn http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
the poem yr arwr ("the hero"), for which hedd wyn won the national eisteddfodd, is still considered the poet's greatest work.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hedd_Wyn http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet
it can be said with certainty that hedd wyn, like his favourite poet shelley, longed for a perfect humanity and a perfect world during the chaos of war.	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hedd_Wyn http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet

horace gray was also the author of the 1898 case united states v. wong kim ark, ruling that "a child born in the united states, of parents of chinese descent, who, at the time of his birth, are subjects of the emperor of china, but have a permanent domicil and residence in the united states, and are there carrying on business, and are not employed in any diplomatic or official capacity under the emperor of china, becomes at the time of his birth a citizen of the united states."	http://dbpedia.org/ontology/birthPlace http://dbpedia.org/resource/Horace_Gray http://dbpedia.org/resource/United_States
